{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598815"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:44:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:44:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15511"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15511"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.28,0.05,0.08,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61675"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8202"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47121"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"3801"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19850"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61675"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of sore throat and fever. She reports feeling very tired and has difficulty swallowing. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. There are enlarged, tender posterior cervical lymph nodes. Her tonsils are enlarged with white exudates. There is no cough.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features is most suggestive of Epstein-Barr virus infection rather than Group A Streptococcal pharyngitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior cervical lymphadenopathy","Absence of cough","Fever above 38\u00b0C","Tonsillar exudates","Palatal petechiae"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents typical features of acute pharyngitis, where the main differential diagnoses are viral (particularly \u003Cem\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/em\u003E) and bacterial (particularly Group A \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E) infections. While there is significant overlap in symptoms, certain features can help distinguish between the two.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior cervical lymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of Epstein-Barr virus infection (infectious mononucleosis). Group A Streptococcal infection typically causes tender anterior cervical lymphadenopathy. The presence of posterior cervical lymphadenopathy, along with fatigue and possible splenomegaly, strongly suggests EBV infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETonsillar exudates\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in both conditions and therefore is not a reliable discriminating feature. The presence of exudates alone cannot differentiate between viral and bacterial causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPalatal petechiae\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen in both conditions and is therefore not helpful in distinguishing between them. They are slightly more common in streptococcal infection but are not specific enough to be diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFever above 38\u00b0C\u003C/strong\u003E is common in both conditions and is not a discriminating feature. Both infections typically cause fever as part of the systemic inflammatory response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsence of cough\u003C/strong\u003E is actually more suggestive of streptococcal pharyngitis. The presence of cough would be more suggestive of a viral cause, though EBV infection often presents without cough.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther features that would support EBV infection include fatigue lasting more than one week, splenomegaly, and generalised lymphadenopathy. Laboratory confirmation can be made with a positive monospot test or EBV-specific serology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epstein-Barr virus typically presents with posterior cervical lymphadenopathy, fatigue, and splenomegaly.","Group A Streptococcus typically presents with tonsillar exudates, tender anterior cervical nodes, and absence of cough.","The presence of palatal petechiae can occur in both conditions and is not reliably discriminatory."],"references":["Huang W, Bai L, Tang H. Epstein-Barr virus infection: the micro and macro worlds. Virol J. 2023 Oct 2;20(1):220. doi: 10.1186/s12985-023-02187-9. PMID: 37784180; PMCID: PMC10546641.","Yu H, Robertson ES. Epstein-Barr Virus History and Pathogenesis. Viruses. 2023 Mar 9;15(3):714. doi: 10.3390/v15030714. PMID: 36992423; PMCID: PMC10056551.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47121"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15511"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47121"},"attributes":{"crea